trans-unit.source: How to use AMQP 1.0 with the Java Service Bus API | Microsoft Azure
trans-unit.target: How to use AMQP 1.0 with the Java Service Bus API | Microsoft Azure

trans-unit.source: Learn how to use the Java Message Service (JMS) with Azure Service Bus and Advanced Message Queuing Protodol (AMQP) 1.0.
trans-unit.target: Learn how to use the Java Message Service (JMS) with Azure Service Bus and Advanced Message Queuing Protodol (AMQP) 1.0.

trans-unit.source: The Advanced Message Queuing Protocol (AMQP) 1.0 is an efficient, reliable, wire-level messaging protocol that can be used to build robust, cross-platform, messaging applications.
trans-unit.target: The Advanced Message Queuing Protocol (AMQP) 1.0 is an efficient, reliable, wire-level messaging protocol that can be used to build robust, cross-platform, messaging applications.

trans-unit.source: AMQP 1.0 support was added to Azure Service Bus in October 2012 and transitioned to General Availability (GA) in May 2013.
trans-unit.target: AMQP 1.0 support was added to Azure Service Bus in October 2012 and transitioned to General Availability (GA) in May 2013.

trans-unit.source: The addition of AMQP 1.0 means that it’s now possible to leverage the queuing and publish/subscribe brokered messaging features of Service Bus from a range of platforms using an efficient binary protocol.
trans-unit.target: The addition of AMQP 1.0 means that it’s now possible to leverage the queuing and publish/subscribe brokered messaging features of Service Bus from a range of platforms using an efficient binary protocol.

trans-unit.source: Furthermore, you can build applications comprised of components built using a mix of languages, frameworks and operating systems.
trans-unit.target: Furthermore, you can build applications comprised of components built using a mix of languages, frameworks and operating systems.

trans-unit.source: This how-to guide explains how to use the Service Bus brokered messaging features (queues and publish/subscribe topics) from Java applications using the popular Java Message Service (JMS) API standard.
trans-unit.target: This how-to guide explains how to use the Service Bus brokered messaging features (queues and publish/subscribe topics) from Java applications using the popular Java Message Service (JMS) API standard.

trans-unit.source: This guide assumes that you already have a Service Bus namespace containing a queue named "queue1."
trans-unit.target: This guide assumes that you already have a Service Bus namespace containing a queue named "queue1."

trans-unit.source: If you do not, then you can create the namespace and queue using the <linkText>Azure Management Portal</linkText><title></title>.
trans-unit.target: If you do not, then you can create the namespace and queue using the <linkText>Azure Management Portal</linkText><title></title>.

trans-unit.source: For more information about how to create Service Bus namespaces and queues, see <linkText>How to Use Service Bus Queues</linkText><title></title>.
trans-unit.target: For more information about how to create Service Bus namespaces and queues, see <linkText>How to Use Service Bus Queues</linkText><title></title>.

trans-unit.source: JMS uses the Java Naming and Directory Interface (JNDI) to create a separation between logical names and physical names.
trans-unit.target: JMS uses the Java Naming and Directory Interface (JNDI) to create a separation between logical names and physical names.

trans-unit.source: Two types of JMS objects are resolved using JNDI: ConnectionFactory and Destination.
trans-unit.target: Two types of JMS objects are resolved using JNDI: ConnectionFactory and Destination.

trans-unit.source: JNDI uses a provider model into which you can plug different directory services to handle name resolution duties.
trans-unit.target: JNDI uses a provider model into which you can plug different directory services to handle name resolution duties.

trans-unit.source: There are no special APIs or options required when using JMS with Service Bus.
trans-unit.target: There are no special APIs or options required when using JMS with Service Bus.

trans-unit.source: However, there are a few restrictions that will be covered later.
trans-unit.target: However, there are a few restrictions that will be covered later.

trans-unit.source: As with any JMS application, the first thing required is configuration of the JNDI environment, to be able to resolve a ConnectionFactory and destinations.
trans-unit.target: As with any JMS application, the first thing required is configuration of the JNDI environment, to be able to resolve a ConnectionFactory and destinations.

trans-unit.source: The JNDI environment is configured by passing a hashtable of configuration information into the constructor of the javax.naming.InitialContext class.
trans-unit.target: The JNDI environment is configured by passing a hashtable of configuration information into the constructor of the javax.naming.InitialContext class.

trans-unit.source: The two required elements in the hashtable are the class name of the Initial Context Factory and the Provider URL.
trans-unit.target: The two required elements in the hashtable are the class name of the Initial Context Factory and the Provider URL.

trans-unit.source: The following restrictions exist when using JMS over AMQP 1.0 with Service Bus, namely:
trans-unit.target: The following restrictions exist when using JMS over AMQP 1.0 with Service Bus, namely:

trans-unit.source: Only one MessageProducer or MessageConsumer is allowed per Session.
trans-unit.target: Only one MessageProducer or MessageConsumer is allowed per Session.

trans-unit.source: If you need to create multiple MessageProducers or MessageConsumers in an application, create a dedicated Session for each of them.
trans-unit.target: If you need to create multiple MessageProducers or MessageConsumers in an application, create a dedicated Session for each of them.

trans-unit.source: Volatile topic subscriptions are not currently supported.
trans-unit.target: Volatile topic subscriptions are not currently supported.

trans-unit.source: MessageSelectors are not currently supported.
trans-unit.target: MessageSelectors are not currently supported.

trans-unit.source: Temporary destinations, i.e., TemporaryQueue, TemporaryTopic are not currently supported, along with the QueueRequestor and TopicRequestor APIs that use them.
trans-unit.target: Temporary destinations, i.e., TemporaryQueue, TemporaryTopic are not currently supported, along with the QueueRequestor and TopicRequestor APIs that use them.

trans-unit.source: Transacted sessions and distributed transactions are not supported.
trans-unit.target: Transacted sessions and distributed transactions are not supported.
